2. SOURCE RULES

Use only public, verifiable sources.

Priority order:

Official central-bank material:
speeches;
statements;
minutes;
monetary policy reports;
press conferences;
parliamentary testimony;
official calendars;
official speaker pages.
High-quality public reporting:
Reuters;
Bloomberg;
WSJ / Nick Timiraos for the Fed;
FT;
CNBC / Yahoo Finance / MarketWatch only when they carry named quotes or interviews;
local central-bank specialist outlets where relevant.
Market pricing:
OIS / futures / swaps if publicly reported;
CME FedWatch for Fed;
market-implied terminal / meeting probabilities if available;
prediction-market probabilities only if clearly labelled as lower-quality / market-color input.
Do not rely on unsourced social media.
Use X / Twitter only for whitelisted institutional reporters or official accounts.
Do not copy proprietary broker research.
If a broker-style template is used as inspiration, reproduce the structure but not proprietary wording.
Direct quotes must be short and selective.

Quote rules:

maximum 15 words per quote;
maximum one direct quote per underlying source in the Weekly Overlay;
paraphrase everything else;
use quotes only when they materially clarify the policy reaction function;
do not use long quote blocks.
For every important point, include:
speaker / institution;
date;
source type;
source URL if available;
confidence level: High / Medium / Low.
Do not use messy concatenated source labels such as:
“Yahoo Finance + 5”;
“WikipediaFederalReserve”;
“KITCOYahoo Finance”;
“BloombergReutersYahoo”.

If the source is not cleanly identified, place the item in Unverified / possible gaps and do not let it drive the final policy read.

3. MANDATORY WINDOW SWEEP PROTOCOL — DO NOT SKIP

Before writing any Chatterbox or Weekly Overlay, perform an explicit window sweep.

The goal is to avoid missing central-bank speeches, interviews, minutes, calendars, official documents or major wire-reported comments.

3.1 Build the relevant speaker roster

For the selected central bank, list the relevant decision-makers before searching.

For the Fed, the roster must include:

Chair;
Vice Chair;
Vice Chair for Supervision;
all Governors;
NY Fed President;
current-year voting regional presidents;
alternate voters if relevant;
high-signal non-voters;
recently replaced or newly appointed officials if they affect the reaction function.

For other central banks, adapt the roster:

ECB: President, Vice President, Executive Board, major NCB governors, known hawks / doves;
BoE: Governor, Deputy Governors, MPC external members;
BoJ: Governor, Deputy Governors, Policy Board;
BoC / RBA / RBNZ / SNB / Riksbank / Norges Bank: Governor, deputies, board / committee members where relevant;
Banxico / BCB / SARB / PBoC: Governor, deputies, board members, minutes, official policy reports and official communication channels.
3.2 Search in four passes

Run the sweep in this order.

Pass 1 — Official sources

Check:

central-bank speech page;
official calendar;
press releases;
minutes;
monetary-policy report;
testimony / hearings;
regional central-bank pages if applicable.

Pass 2 — High-quality wires / media

Check:

Reuters;
Bloomberg;
WSJ / Timiraos for Fed;
FT;
CNBC / Yahoo Finance / MarketWatch only if they carry named quotes or interviews;
local central-bank specialist sources where relevant.

Pass 3 — Individual speaker check

For every roster member, check whether they had:

speech;
interview;
panel;
testimony;
written remarks;
official essay;
media quote;
no public comment.

Pass 4 — Market / institutional context

Only after the official speaker sweep, check:

OIS / futures / meeting pricing;
statement-preview reporting;
blackout-period sourced reporting;
high-quality market commentary if source is clean.
