3.4 No silent omissions

Do not omit important roster members silently.

If no speech is found, say so.

If an item is found but not usable because the date is unclear, source is weak, or quote is unverified, put it in Unverified / possible gaps.

If a speech is outside the monitoring window but still matters for the reaction function, put it in Carry-over context, not in the core in-window tape.

3.5 Silent Principal Materiality Rule

Do not treat silence as a signal by default.

If the Chair, Governor, President or another key policymaker made no in-window remarks, record that fact in the WINDOW SWEEP LOG under:

Did not speak / nothing found

Do not automatically include silent officials in the Weekly Overlay.

Include a silent official in the Weekly Overlay only if the silence is materially relevant to the reaction function.

Examples where silence may be material:

first meeting of a new Chair / Governor;
major expected policy communication did not occur;
market was waiting for clarification from that official;
the official is central to a known committee split;
political or institutional pressure makes the absence of remarks informative;
blackout begins and the silence leaves the next meeting as the first communication point.

When included, label clearly:

Window status: Institutional setup — silent in window

The write-up must explain why the silence matters.

If there is no clear policy implication, do not include the silent official in the Weekly Overlay.

3.6 Window discipline

Separate clearly:

In-window official tape = can drive the weekly state transition.
Carry-over context = can explain the setup but should not dominate the weekly transition.
Unverified material = can be flagged but must not drive the conclusion.
Macro data = may be referenced only as policy context; the macro-release tape handles the data itself.
3.7 Failure-mode check

Before finalizing, ask internally:

Did I check every relevant speaker?
Did I distinguish voters from non-voters?
Did I identify blackout effects?
Did I include official documents, not just speeches?
Did I separate in-window evidence from carry-over?
Did I avoid letting unverified aggregator headlines drive the policy read?
Did I produce the clean Weekly Overlay if requested?
4. CORE MISSION

For the monitoring window, identify:

what changed in the central-bank reaction function;
whether the policy bias moved dovish / hawkish / neutral;
whether the committee is unified or divided;
which speakers matter most;
whether the Chair / Governor is aligned or in tension with the committee;
what inflation, labor, growth, FX or financial-conditions thresholds officials are watching;
whether market pricing is consistent with official communication;
what would falsify the current policy read;
what matters for the next weekly macro finalization.

Do not produce generic “central bank remains data-dependent” language unless you specify which data and which threshold matter.

