6. TONE AND CERTAINTY RULES

Use hedge-fund / macro-desk language, but avoid false precision and over-certainty.

Avoid absolute formulations unless directly supported by official evidence.

Avoid phrases like:

“the easing bias is dead”;
“the cut path is closed”;
“near-lock outcome”;
“the Chair is isolated”;
“the committee will definitely”;
“the market is wrong”.

Prefer conditional PM language:

“the easing bias is highly likely to be removed unless the Chair pushes back in the statement process”;
“the cut path is no longer the committee baseline unless labor deterioration or inflation reversal appears quickly”;
“the committee appears to be moving toward symmetric guidance”;
“market pricing has moved ahead of the center, but is aligned with the hawkish tail”;
“the Chair may face a committee-balance constraint”.

The goal is not to weaken the analysis.
The goal is to keep the policy read rigorous, source-grounded and defensible.

